Sharing Reports as Websites

The default output format for new R Markdown scripts created with RStudio is HTML (with the content saved in a .html file). HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language. This means that the .html files you create with R Markdown can be put online as webpages for others to view!

As it turns out, you can use GitHub not only to host versions of your code repository, but also to serve (display) .html filesâincluding ones generated from R Markdown. Github will host webpages on a publicly accessible web server that can âserveâ the page to anyone who requests it (at a particular URL on the github.io domain). This feature is known as GitHub Pages.

What Is GitHub Pages: https://help.github.com/articles/what-is-github-pages/

Using GitHub Pages involves a few steps. - First, you need to knit your document into a .html file with the name index.htmlâthis is the traditional name for a websiteâs homepage (and the file that will be served at a particular URL by default). - You will need to have pushed this file to a GitHub repository; the index.html file will need to be in the root folder of the repo.

  • Next, you need to configure that GitHub repository to enable GitHub Pages. On the web portal page for your repo, click on the âSettingsâ tab, and scroll down to the section labeled âPagesâ, followed by âGitHub Pages.â From there, you need to specify the âSourceâ of the .html file that Github Pages should serve. Select the âmaster branchâ option to enable GitHub Pages and have it serve the âmasterâ version of your index.html file (see Figure 18.7).

  • Once youâve enabled GitHub Pages, you will be able to view your hosted webpage at the URL (The URL for a website hosted with GitHub Pages)
    • https://GITHUB_USERNAME.github.io/REPO_NAME
    • Replace GITHUB_USERNAME with the username of the account hosting the repo, and REPO_NAME with your repository name.
    • Thus, if you pushed your code to the mkfreeman/report repo on GitHub (stored online at https://github.com/mkfreeman/report), the webpage would be available at https://mkfreeman.github.io/report.
